mtp_project.title: Grady Way BRT Access
mtp_project.description: The project will be a coordinated effort between the City of Renton and WSDOT to improve travel time and BRT access to/from the South Renton Transit Center and the I-405/SR 167 interchange. The project will also provide a connection point to the Rainier Avenue transit corridor which leads to Renton’s key regional growth centers - downtown and Southport/The Landing – via 8th and Garden Avenue North.
mtp_project.planning_process: This project is identified in WSDOT's SR 167 Master Plan and I-405 Master Plan, both of which have been through multiple planning updates since 2005; most recently the SR 167 Master Plan was updated in 2023. The City continues to include this project in its local comprehensive plan, updated in 2025, as well as the City's six-year Transportation Improvement Plan which is updated annually. All of these plans are subject to and have been through various formats of both broad and focused public engagement.
mtp_project.letters_of_concurrence: The City worked with WSDOT and Sen. Hasagawa (11th Leg District) in 2023 toward agency partnership. In 2023, the State Legislature directed funding to WSDOT to complete a preliminary BRT access study.
mtp_project.funds_description: City of Renton staff time in kind

mtp_project.title: Cedar Falls Way Pedestrian Improvements
mtp_project.description: Cedar Falls Way Shared Use path project is approximately 1.0 miles long of 8-foot-wide shared use path paralleling an arterial roadway connecting 436th Ave SE. and North Bend Way into our historic downtown business district.
mtp_project.planning_process: The public planning process for this project is twofold; we have it as a capital improvement plan and in our city's comprehensive plan both approved through public comment, meetings and our city council.

mtp_project.title: West Bremerton Transit Center
mtp_project.description:
his project will develop the Transit Center presently operated by Kitsap Transit near the SR3 Corridor located at the intersection of Bruenn Avenue and Burwell Street
in Bremerton, Washington. Once developed the West Bremerton Transit Center Park & Ride will include approximately five (5) bus berths, pedestrian canopies, a comfort station, a hydrogen fueling facility, and a park & ride accommodating at least 210 vehicles. Additional pedestrian features will include sidewalks/crosswalks, lights, cameras, and bicycle storage to enhance safety and security. 
This is also a location for a possible future Hydrogen Fueling Facility. 
This is a multi-year project that spans beyond the current TIP timeframe.
mtp_project.planning_process:
Kitsap Transit worked closely with the US Navy, the City of Bremerton and the local community to develop the Joint Compatibility Transportation Plan. This Plan identifies the West Bremerton Transit Center and Park & Ride as a key component in the selected alternative adopted by the Bremerton City Council. Webpage is below. Project is listed in Appendix A as # 115. 
https://www.bremertonwa.gov/1356/Joint-Compatibility-Transportation-Plan

mtp_project.title: Fast Ferry Docking Facility - Seattle
mtp_project.description: This project will lead to the establishment of a new passenger-only ferry (POF) regional docking facility in Seattle with a greater capacity for both new and existing POF routes. Work supports effective operation of planned and existing Kitsap Fast Ferry service and may share future POF docking with other agencies. POF service provides faster transportation options for people traveling between the Kitsap Peninsula and downtown Seattle. The project includes the planning, environmental planning/permitting, and preliminary engineering phases associated with constructing a new POF docking facility. Construction would commence after these phases are fully completed.

mtp_project.title: SR 16 Park and Rides
mtp_project.description: A park and ride with 266 spaces serving fixed routes linking to foot ferry service. Mixed land-use options are being included on site.
mtp_project.planning_process:
The project found its origin in the WSDOT sponsored SR 16 Congestion Study: https://wsdot.wa.gov/construction-planning/search-studies/sr-16-tacoma-narrows-bridge-sr-3-congestion-study 
From this Study was a site locational analysis study conducted by Kitsap Transit. This study reached out to the local community seeking assistance on the best location for a future park & ride. Through public feedback, including City Council, Kitsap Transit worked to narrow a set of alternative locations. The preferred location was chosen in 2021 by the Kitsap Transit Board of Commissioners. The need for the park and ride is documented in the above referenced Study and the Kitsap Transit LRTP. Both or which had extensive public outreach efforts.
mtp_project.letters_of_concurrence:
This project is supported by the City of Port Orchard.  See Kitsap Sun article
https://www.kitsapsun.com/story/news/2021/03/07/new-park-and-ride-planned-sidney-road-port-orchard/4602115001/ 
Adopted 2024 Comprehensive Plan Update under the Transportation Element Page 8-8. 
https://portorchardwa.gov/2024-comprehensive-plan-periodic-update/
mtp_project.updated_cost_explanation: The project in the 2022 RTP consisted of four park and ride projects at $32,702,611. However, Kitsap Transit is focused on delivering one park and ride at this time.
